<h1>Honorific &amp; Humble Language</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

@include{{"honorific-humble-verbs-table.inc"}}

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
The speaker is often expected to show respect for other people and Japanese uses three sorts of devices to achieve this:
<ul>
<li> @FORMATION{{@HI{{sonkeigo}} are expressions of respect for another party}}
<li> @FORMATION{{@HI{{kenjougo}} are expressions that the speaker uses to humble himself}}
<li> @FORMATION{{@HI{{teineigo}} are expressions of politeness}}
</ul>
</p>

<h3> @HI{{sonkeigo}} </h3>

<p>
<a href="grammar-sonkeigo.html">@HI{{sonkeigo}}</a> is used when referring to the <em>other</em> party's actions
or state and serves show respect to that party.
</p>

<h2> Examples </h2>

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{in^village}}sanha 7@KJ{{time}}ni @KJ{{come}}raremasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Mr. Nakamura is coming at seven.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{company^long}}ha mou o@KJ{{homecoming}}rini narimashita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      The company president has already left for home.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{douzo @KJ{{seduce}}shi@KJ{{above}}gatte kudasai.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Please help yourselves.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
